The following conditions defined the Alternative Release Scenario #1 pigtail pipe leak at the Edinburg Pump Station No. 1:



$    Failure of flexible connections (pigtails) connected to a 1-ton container resulting in the total release of 2,000 pounds of chlorine;



$    Release of the entire amount as a gas in 30 minutes;



$    Use of the one-hour average ERPG-2 as the toxic endpoint;



$    Consideration of the population residing within a full circle with a radius corresponding to the toxic endpoint distance; and



$    USEPA mandated meteorological conditions, specifically a D atmospheric stability class, wind speed of 3 m/sec., and an air temperature of 77? F.



Atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Alternative Release Scenario resulted in a chlorine toxic endpoint distance of 0.2 miles and a potential affected residential population of 768. The program RMP*Comp32, provided by the USEPA, performed the calculations. The USEPA program LandView6 calculated the population estimates.



